Predicting Selling Price of a House

1 Background

In this project I will develop a model to predict the selling price of a given home in Ames, Iowa. My aim here is to figure out whether the asking/current price of the house is higher or lower than the true value of the house. If the home is undervalued, it can be considered a good investment.

2 Training Data and relevant packages

In order to better assess the quality of the model I have divided the data randomly into three separate pieces: a training data set, a testing data set, and a validation data set. Before we proceed further I will give a brief about the data set.

TYPE: Population SIZE: 2930 observations, 82 variables

DESCRIPTIVE ABSTRACT: Data set contains information from the Ames Assessor’s Office used in computing assessed values for individual residential properties sold in Ames, IA from 2006 to 2010.

VARIABLE DESCRIPTIONS: The data has 82 columns which include 23 nominal, 23 ordinal, 14 discrete, and 20 continuous variables (and 2 additional observation identifiers). Some of the important varibales have been explained below - Lot Area (Continuous): Lot size in square feet

  • Utilities (Ordinal): Type of utilities available, 4 classifications

  • Neighborhood (Nominal): Physical locations within Ames city limits, 27 values

  • Overall Qual (Ordinal): Rates the overall material and finish of the house, 10 classifications from 1-10

  • Overall Cond (Ordinal): Rates the overall condition of the house, 10 classifications from 1-10

  • Year Built (Discrete): Original construction date

  • Total Bsmt SF (Continuous): Total square feet of basement area

  • Heating (Nominal): Type of heating, 6 values

  • 1st Flr SF (Continuous): First Floor square feet

  • 2nd Flr SF (Continuous) : Second floor square feet

  • Garage Area (Continuous): Size of garage in square feet

  • Garage Qual (Ordinal): Garage quality, 6 classifications

  • Pool Area (Continuous): Pool area in square feet

  • SalePrice (Continuous): Sale price

First I’ll the load training data set.

load("ames_train.Rdata")

Next; import all the appropriate packages.

library(dplyr)

dplyr: For exploratory data analysis and manipulation. ggplot2: For making plots. stats: For statistical calculations. BAS: For Bayesian Model Averaging and Model Selection.

3 Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

3.1 Trimming the data set

It is very important to explore the structure of the data and the relationships between the variables in the data set before starting modelling. For example, we might need to transform some variables, remove the NA/Empty values from the dataset.

Therefore, first I’ll look at the price because since it is a continuous variable which has a very wide range, it might need to be transformed.

ggplot(ames_train, aes(x=price)) + geom_bar(binwidth = 600,fill = "#013B23")
## Warning: `geom_bar()` no longer has a `binwidth` parameter. Please use
## `geom_histogram()` instead.

The distribution is right skewed, and hence we tranform it to log(price).

ames_train<- ames_train %>% mutate(log_price=log(price))

Before we proceed with the EDA, we should assess the number of NA values in each varibale.

4 Development and Assessment of an Initial model

Before we start modelling we need to make sure that the ames_Test and ames_Train data set have the same variables with the same levels and to ensure that we’ll define a function called modify.

ModifyDataSet <- function(x) { x %>%
    
filter(Sale.Condition %in% c("Normal","Partial")) %>% filter(Foundation!="Wood")%>%
    filter(Neighborhood != "Landmrk") %>% filter(House.Style!="2.5Fin")%>%
    mutate(Bsmt.Qual=ifelse(is.na(Bsmt.Qual),"Missing",Bsmt.Qual))
           
}
ames_train1 <- ModifyDataSet(ames_train)

4.5 Overfitting

The process of building a model generally involves starting with an initial model , identifying its shortcomings, and adapting the model accordingly. This process may be repeated several times until the model fits the data reasonably well. However, the model may do well on training data but perform poorly out-of-sample (meaning, on a dataset other than the original training data) because the model is overly-tuned to specifically fit the training data. This is called “overfitting.” To determine whether overfitting is occurring on a model, we compare the performance of a model on both in-sample and out-of-sample data sets. To look at performance of my initial model on out-of-sample data, I will use the data set ames_test.

load("ames_test.Rdata")

I’ll find the RMSE value of our model using test file and compare it with the value we got earlier from the train data.

But before data we need to perfom all the operations we performed on training data set to the testing data set and also add the variables we created.

ames_test1<-ModifyDataSet(ames_test)
Testing.resid <- ames_test1$price - exp(predict(Initial_Model.AIC, ames_test1))
Testing.rmse <- sqrt(mean(Testing.resid^2))
Testing.rmse
## [1] 25510.67
Testing.resid <- ames_test1$price - exp(predict(Initial_Model.BIC, ames_test1))
Testing.rmse <- sqrt(mean(Testing.resid^2))
Testing.rmse
## [1] 25444.71

It is usually expected that since the model fits the training data better, the RMSE value for the training data set would be smaller than RMSE value for the testing data set but in our case the situation is different.

In our case the RMSE for the Test Data is less than the Train data.

5.2 Variable Interaction

I did not include any vaiable interations in my model but there are chances of varible intereaction in this dataset.

5.3 Variable Selection

I used stepwise AIC and BIC to find the best model. I used this method beacuse they are based on the importance of a variable which is measured by p-value.

ggplot(data = ames_train, aes(x = Bsmt.Qual, y =Bsmt.Cond))+ geom_jitter(color = "black")

ggplot(data = ames_train, aes(x = Overall.Qual, y =Overall.Cond))+ geom_jitter(color = "black")

If we had included both Bsmt.Qual and Bsmt.Cond in our model then we might have had a problem . The independent variables included in the model should not depend on any other variable in the model.

5.4 Model Testing

There were many variables which had differnt levels in testing and training data set and therfore we had to define a function first which only considered the fixed number of levels in a variable. For eg. Training Data set no value in level called Wood in Foundation but the Testing data did, which created error while testing the model. Same way for Landmrk in Neighbourhood and 2.5Fin in House.Style.

6.2 Final Model RMSE

Final_Model.AIC.resid <- ames_train1$price - exp(predict(Final_Model.AIC, ames_train1))
Final_Model.AIC.rmse <- sqrt(mean(Final_Model.AIC.resid^2))
Final_Model.AIC.rmse
## [1] 27097.95

Compared to the RMSE for initial model the RMSE has substantially reduced. This justifies that the Final model is the better model.

Testing.Final.resid <- ames_test1$price - exp(predict(Final_Model.AIC, ames_test1))
Testing.Final.rmse <- sqrt(mean(Testing.Final.resid^2))
Testing.Final.rmse
## [1] 23509.44

Even the RMSE for testing data has drastically reduced. But still the RMSE for testing data set is lower than RMSE for training data set.

6.3 Final Model Evaluation

Strenghts: The R square value of my final model is .9049 which is preety good and hence my model can be used to predict data. The RMSE value for Testing is lower than that for Training which is not usual but that means that my model is not overfitting the data.

Weakness:I have adapted/changes the Testing data according to the training data and hence I won’t be able to predict value for a house from the testing data set with Neighbourhood as Landmrk or a house with House.Style as 2.5Fin or a House with Foundation as Wood.

Interval_95 <- predict(Final_Model.AIC, ames_validation1, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
Coverage.Prob.95 <- mean(exp(ames_validation1$log_price) > exp(Interval_95[,"lwr"]) & (exp(ames_validation1$log_price)) < exp(Interval_95[,"upr"]))
Coverage.Prob.95
## [1] 0.9616963

This means that 96.2% of the predicted home prices from the validation data set are in the 95% confidence interval of the actual home price.

Coverage Probability of 96% means that our model is good.

7 Conclusion

Even though logically Bath seemed like a very important variable but when compared to other varibles it is ignored.

In Linear modelling, most important step is Explaraoty Data Analysis.

Before starting modelling, it is very important to check whether we should transform any variable or not.

While creating a big model which is supposed to be used for predicting some values, it is very important to be thorough with the levels in each variable so you can easily adapt your data according to the testing data set.

We started with 10 varaibles in the Initial model and by doing stepwise AIC and BIC, we reduced the number of varibles to 9.

We started with 15 varaibles in the Final model and by doing stepwise AIC and BIC, we reduced the number of varibles to 13.
